Jules Reciprocal Source License v1.0 (JRSL-1.0 experimental)

Jules is built on the principle that high-performance infrastructure must remain transparent, auditable, and community-stewarded. This license grants broad freedoms to individuals, researchers, small organizations, and non-commercial users. However, to ensure the long-term sustainability of the commons, Large Commercial Entities are required to contribute their improvements back to the project.

Note: This is not an Open Source Initiative (OSI) approved license. It is a source-available license with reciprocal obligations for qualifying commercial entities.

1. Definitions

1.1 “Software”
The Jules compiler, runtime, optimization passes, self-repair engine, JIT tiers, AoT system, standard library, tools, and all associated source code and assets released by Open Intelligence under this license.

1.2 “Derivative Work”
Any modification, extension, fork, or work that is based on the Software and incorporates substantial portions of its source code. For the avoidance of doubt, separate modules or applications that merely link to or invoke the Software via standard public APIs without incorporating source code from the Software are not considered Derivative Works.

1.3 “Improvement”
Any change, addition, bug fix, or optimization made directly to the source code of the Software or its Derivative Works.

1.4 “Qualifying Organization”
Any legal entity (including its parent companies, subsidiaries, affiliates, and controlled entities) whose consolidated gross annual revenue exceeded $10,000,000 USD in the preceding 12-month fiscal period, calculated according to standard GAAP/IFRS rules.

1.5 “Upstream Contribution”
A complete pull request submitted to the official Open Intelligence repository containing the Improvement, properly licensed under JRSL-1.0, with tests and documentation where applicable.

1.6 “Corresponding Source”
For a Derivative Work, the Corresponding Source means all the source code needed to generate, install, and run the Derivative Work (excluding system libraries and tools). It does not include source code for independent applications that merely use the Software via standard interfaces.

2. Grant of Rights
Subject to the terms of this license, Open Intelligence grants you a perpetual, worldwide, non-exclusive, royalty-free, irrevocable (except as provided in Section 7) copyright and patent license to:
Use, copy, modify, and distribute the Software.
Create and distribute Derivative Works.

2.1 Rights for Individuals and Non-Qualifying Organizations
If you are an individual or a Non-Qualifying Organization, you may exercise these rights without further obligations. You may distribute Derivative Works under any license of your choice, including proprietary or closed-source licenses, provided you retain all copyright notices and disclaimers present in the original Software.

3. Obligations for Qualifying Organizations
If you are a Qualifying Organization, or if you become one, you must comply with the following obligations for any Derivative Work created or used after the date you become a Qualifying Organization.

3.1 Grandfather Clause
If you were a Non-Qualifying Organization when you first created or deployed a specific Derivative Work, you may continue to use, modify, and distribute that specific version of the Derivative Work under the terms applicable at the time of its creation, even if you later become a Qualifying Organization. However, any new Derivative Works created or significant new modifications made after becoming a Qualifying Organization must comply with Sections 3.2 and 3.3.

3.2 Public Release Requirement
Within 30 days of the earlier of (a) internal production deployment, (b) external distribution, or (c) offering the Derivative Work as a service, you must:
Publish the complete Corresponding Source of the Derivative Work under JRSL-1.0.
Host it in a publicly accessible Git repository with full history and clear attribution to Open Intelligence.

3.3 Mandatory Upstream Contribution
Every Improvement made to the Software itself must be submitted as an Upstream Contribution within 14 days of its creation or internal adoption (whichever is earlier). The contribution must include:
Full source code.
Relevant tests.
Documentation of the change.

3.4 Anti-Circumvention
You may not circumvent these obligations by:
Using shell companies, subsidiaries, or affiliated entities to artificially stay under the $10M revenue threshold (revenue is calculated on a fully consolidated basis).
Having employees or contractors create or use Derivative Works through personal accounts or third-party repositories to avoid the obligations of this section.

4. Compliance & Certification

4.1 Compliance Page
Qualifying Organizations must maintain a public webpage listing their Jules-based deployments and links to their Upstream Contributions.

4.2 Certification of Compliance
Upon reasonable written notice from Open Intelligence alleging non-compliance, a Qualifying Organization must provide a written certification signed by an officer of the company stating that they are in compliance with Section 3. Open Intelligence reserves the right to request this certification no more than once per calendar year.

4.3 Dispute Resolution
If Open Intelligence disputes the certification, the parties agree to attempt good-faith negotiation for 30 days. If unresolved, the matter may be subject to binding arbitration in accordance with the laws specified in Section 9.

5. Patent Retaliation
If you or any of your affiliates initiate patent litigation against Open Intelligence or any contributor alleging that the Software itself infringes your patents, then any patent licenses granted to you under this License for that Software shall terminate immediately. This clause does not apply to patent litigation regarding other products or services unrelated to the Software.

6. Termination
Rights under this license terminate automatically upon material breach.
Cure Period: For unintentional breaches, you have a 30-day period to cure the breach after receiving notice. If cured, your rights are reinstated retroactively.
Effect of Termination: Upon termination, you must cease all distribution of the Derivative Work and remove public copies, except for copies that were already released in full compliance with Section 3 prior to termination.

